12 (a) American Sign Language;
13 (b) English-based manual or sign systems;
14 (c) Oral and aural communication;
15 (d) Spoken and written English, including speech reading or lip
16 reading; and
17 (e) Communication with assistive technology devices.
18 2. “Dyslexia” means a neurological learning disability
19 characterized by difficulties with accurate and fluent word
20 recognition and poor spelling and decoding abilities that typically
21 result from a deficit in the phonological component of language.
22 3. “Dyslexia intervention” means systematic, multisensory
23 intervention offered in an appropriate setting that is derived from
24 evidence-based research.
25 4. “Individualized education program” has the meaning
26 ascribed to it in 20 U.S.C. § 1414(d)(1)(A).
27 5. “Individualized education program team” has the meaning
28 ascribed to it in 20 U.S.C. § 1414(d)(1)(B).
29 6. “Provider of special education” means a school within a
30 school district or charter school that provides education or services
31 to pupils with disabilities or any other entity that is responsible for
32 providing education or services to a pupil with a disability for a
33 school district or charter school.
34 7. “Pupil who receives early intervening services” means a
35 person enrolled in kindergarten or grades 1 to 12, inclusive, who is
36 not a pupil with a disability but who needs additional academic and
37 behavioral support to succeed in a regular school program.
38 8. “Pupil with a disability” means a “child with a disability,” as
39 that term is defined in 20 U.S.C. § 1401(3)(A), who is under 22
40 years of age.
41 9. “Response to scientific, research-based intervention” means
42 a collaborative process which assesses a pupil’s response to
43 scientific, research-based intervention that is matched to the needs
44 of a pupil and that systematically monitors the level of performance
45 and rate of learning of the pupil over time for the purpose of making
